description:
**GENERAL STATEMENT OF DUTIES****:** Helps school teachers by assisting in routine non-teaching duties including pupil supervision; does related work as required.

 **DISTINGUISHING FEATURES OF THE CLASS****:** This is work of ordinary difficulty involving responsibility for assisting teachers by performing assigned routine tasks including the supervision and care of children. Since there are definite limits on the type and complexity of assignments, the class of School Monitor differs in that respect from Teacher Aide which usually involves duties of greater difficulty generally requiring specific skills or abilities.

 **EXAMPLES OF WORK:** (Illustrative only)


Assists Teachers in supervising recreation and Lunch periods and study halls;


Guides children safely across streets and intersections;


Maintains order in gymnasiums, locker rooms, and swimming pools;


Oversees students passing between classes and in locker rooms and on premises before and after school;


Issues athletic supplies and equipment;


Helps children in lower grades with wearing apparel;


May perform simple clerical duties under close supervision;


May render elementary first—aid treatment

 **REQUIRED KNOWLEDGES, SKILLS AND ABILITIES****:** Good general intelligence; ability to get along well with children and command their respect; some knowledge of first aid methods; clerical aptitude; neat personal appearance; familiarity with classroom routine; good powers of observation; tact; courtesy; good judgment; good physical condition.

 **ACCEPTABLE EXPERIENCE AND TRAINING:**


None required, but completion of a grade school course and experience with children are desirable.



Adopted CSC Resolution 10/2/67

**The Chapel School (TCS) Job Description for Teacher**
Each teacher at The Chapel School, under the direct supervision of the Principal, is responsible for teaching academics and religion to their students unless departmentalization dictates otherwise, including instruction, motivation, evaluation and all other aspects of teaching. TCS Teachers are expected to maintain effective working relationships with VLC Pastors, TCS Administrators, other teachers, maintenance staff, support staff and all other members of the VLC/TCS Community. TCS Teachers are expected to maintain a safe, nurturing, Christ-centered environment for students at school and provide positive and professional support to TCS families as needed, always maintaining alignment with our mission ... "To Know, Live and Share the Love of Christ".
**Qualifications**
All TCS Teachers are to be certified (preferably by the State of New York) or working toward certification. Certification must meet the requirements put forth by NYS Department of Education (DOE), and a copy of each certificate or license should be kept on file in the school office.
All TCS Teachers are expected to acquire a NYS Teacher's Certificate within 24 months of employment. Certificates must be maintained and renewed according to the standards set by the NYS DOE. An annual written request for exception must be presented to and approved by the administration.
**Responsibilities**
It is understood that all TCS Teachers will:
* Participate in scheduled team and full faculty meetings;
* Attend all scheduled school functions;
* Be on campus by 7:45 AM each school day, unless otherwise determined by the administration;
* Prepare daily and weekly instructional plans that align with standards (currently Common Core);
* Plan age-appropriate, Christ-centered, faith-integrated lessons that align with academic standards and the mission of TCS;
* Plan and coordinate field trips;
* Establish a trusting relationship with students and families;
* Integrate technology and other modern techniques to maximize student engagement;
* Maintain an inspiring and organized classroom;
* Maintain a creative and attractive learning environment;
* Recognize and reinforce the importance of good conduct and achievement by students;
* Use effective and varied assessments to monitor student achievement;
* Counsel students or direct them to the Guidance Counselor as needed;
* Administer iReady Math/Reading Assessments and utilize results to enhance student development;
* Establish classroom rules for classroom management and discipline;
* Be fair and consistent in following through on classroom/school rules;
* Use a balance of Law and Gospel in discipline, focusing on a cycle of forgiveness;
* Respond to the individual physical, emotional and spiritual needs of the children;
* Communicate expectations effectively with the children and respond appropriately and consistently when expectations are met (or not met);
* Be flexible when unusual situations/needs arise;
* Maintain student records (grade books, report cards, attendance, etc.) appropriately;
* Practice Shelter Plan and Evacuation Drills with students and maintain student safety in all circumstances;
* Establish and maintain regular communication with families with regard to academic and/or behavioral concerns.
* Supervise the classroom, lunch room, hallway, playground and outside venues on field trips to maintain (as assigned) student safety;
* Assist with special events (Chapel Services, concerts, PTO events, etc.) as needed;
* Dress professionally but comfortably unless special circumstance arises (field trips, etc.);
* Dismiss their classes on time and supervise dismissal according to school policy/procedures;
* Arrive at school on time and stay until their duties are completed. K-8 Teachers should leave no earlier than 3:45 PM (Monday-Thursday) or 3:30 PM (Fridays). Preschool Teachers should remain on site for 30 minutes beyond designated dismissal times;
* Offer extra help to their students before or after school hours at least one day per week;
* Review and understand all information in the Faculty/Staff and Family Handbooks; and,
* Monitor and approve the time cards of any teacher aides that might assist them directly.


Salary depends on education and experience per the Atlantic District Scale.
Please send cover letter and resume to Principal Michael Schultz at mschultz@thechapelschool.org.
